\begin{remark}[Finite-subspanning reduction]\label{rem:basic_open_cech_finite_subspanning}
  Although the hypothesis $\langle s\rangle = \mathcal O_C(U)$ does not restrict $s$ to be finite, the unit element $1 \in \mathcal O_C(U)$ is witnessed by a finite $\mathcal O_C(U)$-linear combination of elements of $s$. There exists therefore a finite subset $s_0 \subseteq s$ with $\langle s_0\rangle = \mathcal O_C(U)$. The two covers $\mathfrak U = \{D(f)\}_{f \in s}$ and $\mathfrak U_0 = \{D(f)\}_{f \in s_0}$ then satisfy $\bigsqcup_{f \in s} D(f) = U = \bigsqcup_{f \in s_0} D(f)$ (both spanning conditions yield $U$ itself), and the inclusion of index sets $s_0 \hookrightarrow s$ induces a refinement map of cochain complexes $C^\bullet(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_C) \to C^\bullet(\mathfrak U_0, \mathcal O_C)$ obtained by precomposing each multi-index with the inclusion. Because both covers generate the same sieve on $U$, this refinement map is a quasi-isomorphism; it suffices therefore to prove acyclicity for $\mathfrak U_0$. After this reduction, every cochain factor at degree $n$ is a \emph{finite} product indexed by $s_0^{n+1}$, and the product-localisation commutation in Step~2 holds (Mathlib's \texttt{IsLocalizedModule.pi} requires a finite indexing set, so the reduction to $s_0$ is what makes the standard textbook argument formalisable).
\end{remark}
